<p>The <code>trace</code> tag enables detailed execution tracing.</p>

<h2>Syntax</h2>
<pre>{open}trace{close}
  Code to trace
{open}/trace{close}</pre>

<h2>What It Does</h2>
<p>The trace tag enables PAD's tracing mode for the enclosed content. This records:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Every tag processed</li>
  <li>Variable changes</li>
  <li>Level transitions</li>
  <li>Timing information</li>
</ul>

<h2>Example Usage</h2>
<pre>{open}trace{close}
  {open}set x=1{close}
  {open}increment $x{close}
  {open}$x{close}
{open}/trace{close}</pre>
<p>This would trace each operation within the block.</p>

<h2>Trace Output</h2>
<p>When tracing is enabled, PAD outputs detailed information about:</p>
<table>
  <tr><th>Item</th><th>Description</th></tr>
  <tr><td>Tag name</td><td>Which tag is being processed</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Parameters</td><td>Tag parameters and options</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Level</td><td>Current nesting level</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Result</td><td>What the tag returned</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Time</td><td>Processing duration</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>Configuration</h2>
<p>Tracing can also be enabled globally via config:</p>
<pre>$padInfo = 'trace';</pre>

<h2>When to Use</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Understanding complex template execution</li>
  <li>Finding performance bottlenecks</li>
  <li>Debugging unexpected behavior</li>
  <li>Learning how PAD processes templates</li>
</ul>

<h2>Warning</h2>
<p style="color:orange">Tracing significantly impacts performance. Only use during development and debugging.</p>
